Market Entry Strategy · Three Plays

FORTÉ

Co-sell. Subcontract. Compete. All three are on the table.

FORTÉ (formerly AVI Systems) is the #1 AV integrator in North America — $576M revenue, 42 US locations, 1,500 employee-owners, deep Chicago F500 relationships. They transform rooms with screens. What they can't do is the physical branded environment surrounding the technology. That's Foxmark's opening — and it works three different ways.

Play 1 · Co-Sell
Mutual Referral
FORTÉ walks into a Chicago F500 for AV. Client asks about the walls, floor, lobby graphics. FORTÉ refers Foxmark and expands their own scope. Foxmark does the same in reverse when environmental graphics clients need AV.
Win-win. Low friction to start.
Play 2 · Subcontract
FORTÉ Subs Foxmark
Client wants a complete space. FORTÉ owns the client relationship and subs Foxmark for the physical environment. Foxmark gets access to accounts — Chase, Walgreens, United — it would take years to build into cold.
Foxmark gets in the room. Fast.
Play 3 · Compete
Out-Scope Them
When a client wants a complete branded environment and calls FORTÉ first, FORTÉ has to stop at the screen. Foxmark can deliver the full space — physical and digital layer — by partnering with a different AV integrator. Complete scope beats partial scope.
Foxmark wins the whole job.
What FORTÉ Can't Do
FORTÉ installs a $250K video wall in a Walgreens regional HQ lobby.
The wall behind it? Bare drywall.
The floor, windows, wayfinding? Untouched.
Their scope ends at the bezel.
Foxmark wraps the entire environment around it — murals, window film, floor graphics, dimensional brand marks — so the space tells a complete story.
No Chicago competitor does both.
Bottom Line: The goal isn't necessarily to make FORTÉ a partner. The goal is to get inside their accounts — by whatever route opens first. Co-sell if they're willing. Subcontract if they need help. Compete directly if the opportunity is there.

Partner Strategy — How It Fits Together
→
NIT first. Default every install job to the primary relationship. Protects quality, simplifies billing, builds NIT's dependency on Foxmark volume.
→
Bench for overflow. B5 (union buildings), GII (architectural film), My-SignGuy (suburban volume). Activates when NIT is at capacity or a project requires specialist skills.
→
Co-sell for pipeline. A&D firms and GCs are the highest-leverage referral channel. One relationship seeds 5–10 enterprise clients. Pursue Gensler and Leopardo in Year 1.

Competitive Intelligence · Chicago Metro

Where Foxmark
Wins the Room.

14 competitors in the Chicagoland commercial graphics market mapped across six capability dimensions. Foxmark is the only player delivering integrated branded environments, rapid in-house production, eco-certified materials, and program-level rollout management from a single local Chicago studio.

Competitor Intelligence · Deep Dives

What Chicago's
Top Rivals Reveal.

Four competitors studied in depth. Each reveals a strategic lesson that directly shapes the Foxmark Chicago Studio playbook and validates our model.

Cushing
Est. 1929 · Branded Environments · Chicago
Key Lesson
Nearly a century of environmental graphics and branded environments work. Strong AEC client base — architects, contractors, corporations. Foxmark's advantage: faster production cycles, eco-certified materials, and AI-accelerated design they can't match. Cushing is the interior-focused competitor to watch most closely.
Parvin-Clauss
Est. 1952 · Exterior Signage · Maywood IL HQ
Key Lesson
70+ year Chicago institution, family-owned, strong exterior fabrication and national programs. Primarily exterior-focused — limited interior branded environment capability. Validates Foxmark's interior-first positioning. Their maintenance program (Sign Armor) shows value of recurring revenue — a model to replicate.
SpeedPro Chicago Loop
Top 10% Nationally · Franchise · Loop
Key Lesson
Recovered from near-bankruptcy through consultative ROI-based selling and 60–75% margins on bundled services. Validates our phased go-to-market with pre-launch pilots and our margin targets. Their franchise model limits multi-site program management — Foxmark's HQ integration is a decisive advantage here.
Cima Network
Inc. 5000 · National Programs · Chicago Area
Key Lesson
National rollout specialist — Topgolf, Pep Boys, Regal Entertainment. Full-service: fabrication, install, digital integration, maintenance. Their strength is large national programs; their gap is local Chicago responsiveness and eco-certified interior materials. A referral partner opportunity for overflow program work.
Foxmark Advantage

Four Strengths.
Four Competitor Gaps.

🏢 Interior Environments Leadership
Most Chicago competitors — Parvin-Clauss, FASTSIGNS, Windy City Signs — are exterior-signage focused. Foxmark's core strength is transforming interior spaces into branded environments: wall murals, glass branding, wayfinding. Highest-margin, fastest-growing segment in Chicago.
⚡ Single-Workflow Integration
Design → Production → Installation in one workflow. No handoffs. Competitors either fabricate (and sub out install) or install (and sub out production). Foxmark does both — backed by HQ's 100,000+ sq ft manufacturing and New Image Technologies as Chicago install partner.
🌱 Eco-Certified as Standard
PVC-free materials, low-VOC inks, recyclable substrates as standard — not an add-on. Increasingly required in enterprise RFPs from Fortune 500 sustainability teams. Only Graphic Partners offers comparable eco options, but without the interior environment focus or installation capability.
🏠 Local Studio + National HQ Scale
Chicago delivers faster-than-national-vendor service for local programs. HQ's 100,000+ sq ft absorbs national overflow. Perfect for Walgreens, Jewel, Chase, and Aldi — chains needing local speed and national scale that nationals like Identiti can't match locally.
Competitor Gaps = Foxmark Opportunities
🚫 Sign Companies Don't Do Interiors
Chicago's 50+ sign companies — Parvin-Clauss, FASTSIGNS, Windy City Signs — are built around exterior fabrication. When a Fortune 500 needs to transform a lobby, campus, or retail fleet interior, most local vendors simply can't do it end-to-end.
🚫 Nationals Are Slow and Expensive Locally
Cima Network, Identiti, and Jones Sign are optimized for large national rollouts, not responsive local service. Store-by-store Chicago work gets quoted high and delivered slow. Foxmark's studio captures exactly this gap.
🚫 Printers Aren't Installers
Graphic Partners and Chicago Print Group produce quality wide-format print — but neither offers installation or branded environment design. Clients must source three vendors. Foxmark's single-workflow model eliminates this entirely.
🚫 No One Combines Eco + Enterprise Scale
Cushing does branded environments. Graphic Partners does eco printing. No Chicago competitor combines both at enterprise program scale with HQ manufacturing backup. This is Foxmark's clearest white space in the market.
